Hitler's rise to power began in the aftermath of World War I, when Germany faced economic hardship and political instability. He capitalized on the public's dissatisfaction with the existing government and established the National Socialist German Workers' Party (Nazis) in 1920. His charismatic leadership and populist appeals helped him gain support from various segments of society, including the working class, middle-class Germans, and even some members of the military.

In 1933, Hitler became Chancellor of Germany, and in 1934, he consolidated his power by becoming Führer ("leader") of the Nazi Party and head of state. Under his rule, Germany embarked on a campaign of expansion and conquest, invading neighboring countries and eventually starting World War II in 1939.

During the war, Hitler's regime implemented a policy of genocide against Jews, Roma, Slavs, and others deemed "undesirable" by the Nazis. This resulted in the systematic murder of millions of people in concentration camps, such as Auschwitz and Dachau.
